ar regulatory adjustments. This is particularly important given the complexity and scale of Medicare Part D operations [Data: Entities (27), Relationships (57)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Statutory mandates override the calendar year restriction\",\n            \"explanation\": \"While 42 CFR § 423.516 generally prohibits mid-year implementation of new, significant regulatory requirements, it includes an exception: such requirements may be implemented outside the calendar year start if mandated by statute. This exception ensures that urgent or legally required changes can be enacted without delay, preserving the integrity of federal law. However, this also introduces a potential point of variability, as statutory mandates may not always align with the predictable rhythm of the calendar year. The existence of this exception underscores the balance between regulatory stability and legal necessity [Data: Entities (27), Relationships (57)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The relationship between 42 CFR § 423.516 and the Calendar Year is structurally interdependent\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Calendar Year and 42 CFR § 423.516 are structurally interdependent, with the regulation relying on the Calendar Year as its temporal anchor. Without the Calendar Year as a defined time period, the rule’s enforcement would lack a clear reference point. Conversely, the Calendar Year gains regulatory significance through its role in enforcing the timing constraints of 42 CFR § 423.516. This interdependence creates a stable, cyclical regulatory framework that supports long-term planning and compliance in the Medicare Part D program. The relationship is not merely descriptive but functional, shaping the operational reality of PDP Sponsors [Data: Entities (35, 27), Relationships (57)].\"\n        }\n    ],\n    \"rating\": 7.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the critical role of the Calen